Allen East Student Council has created these signs to spread positivity and community amongst our high school students!
They have been randomly put in the yard of 6 high school students.
Receivers of the signs are instructed to do the following:
- Sign your name on the back
- Take a pic of you with your sign and post on social media with #ivebeenshood #shooawaycovidblues
Put the sign in another HS student's yard within 24 hours.
Return to AE Schools High School office in June.

Wanted: Class of 2020
The Lima News is planning its Salute to Graduates publication, a special section that recognizes the area’s graduating high school seniors.

To help shine a positive light on the Class of 2020 in a year that is decidedly different, we are welcoming photos to be submitted of the seniors.

To participate, here are some tips:

• Seniors should wear their cap and gown, if available.

• Have someone in the household take a photo of the senior’s head and shoulders. (Tassel goes on the right, because the student has not graduated yet.)

• Email the photo to amcgeesterrett@aimmediamidwest.com, subject line “Senior Salute.” Be sure to include the senior’s name, school, name of the college or program they will enter and major, or what their future plans entail.

Deadline is 5 p.m. Monday, May 18.

post_text: The Ohio Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services (OhioMHAS) joined with Governor Mike DeWine and RecoveryOhio to launch a new, toll-free Careline to provide emotional support for Ohioans who are experiencing stress, anxiety, fear, sadness and loneliness amid the COVID-19 pandemic. Ohioans may call 1-800-720-9616 to connect with trained counselors for 24/7 support. The Careline is staffed by credentialed counselors who have been trained to provide free, confidential support for a wide range of needs, including mental health concerns, substance use, problem gambling, and more. Individuals experiencing an acute crisis can still reach out to the Ohio Crisis Text Line (keyword 4HOPE to 741 741) or the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline (1-800-273-8255). Find more information, and sample social media posts, at http://mha.ohio.gov/careline.

post_text:
From Mrs. Burgei for STEM students:

Call to action!

A hospital has reached out to our STEM students. Let’s see if we can use our creativity to help them!

Challenge
The hospital has run out of face shields and need some designs for face shields made out of materials you can find at home. Your challenge is to build a face shield made of materials you can find around your house. This is just a prototype, so if you do not have a clear piece of plastic for the actual "shield" part, you can use a piece of plain paper to show where it would be.

Criteria:
-Made out of everyday objects
-Acetate (clear plastic piece) far enough from face that it is not touching your face
-Stays on head without falling off or being held on
-Fits different adult head sizes without being too loose or tight
-Keeps germs/droplets from getting on face
-Washable (no cloth)

Deliverables:
Email Mrs. Burgei (burgeim@alleneastschool.org) a picture or description of your idea

Timeline:
On Friday, I will forward your ideas on. This is BIG. You could save lots of lives with your idea!
